The key details of the study include:  - **Participants**: The study encompasses 82 adult burn patients admitted to the ICU. - **Randomization**: Participants were randomly assigned to either an intervention group or a control group in a 1:1 ratio. The intervention group received standard care in addition to a maximum of six Music therapy sessions provided by a certified music therapist over a 2-week period. - **Electrophysiological Measures**: Electrophysiological measures were taken from a subset of 9 participants in the intervention group (11%). - **Ethics and Registration**: The study was approved by the ethics committee of the Fundación Santa Fe de Bogotá (FSFB) with approval IDs CCEI-11234-2019 and CCEI-11971-2020. metadata.studyDesign: This dataset presents a comprehensive record from a multi-session brain–machine interface (BMI) training study involving seven healthy adult participants (four male, three female), aged between 20 and 30 years (Mean = 24.3, SD = 3.8). The study focused on both open-loop and closed-loop control of a lower-limb exoskeleton (Rex Bionics) using EEG data. Each participant completed nine sessions, scheduled two to three times per week depending on availability. Every session was structured into two distinct phases: a Training Phase, during which participants practiced motor imagery tasks to calibrate the decoder, and a Trial Phase, in which they engaged in closed-loop BMI control to initiate or halt walking. EEG recordings were acquired using 60 scalp electrodes and 4 EOG channels, alongside motion data collected via inertial measurement unit (IMU) sensors mounted on the participant’s forehead and the back brace of the exoskeleton. Decoder feedback and control signals were logged to evaluate BMI responsiveness and gait transitions. Following the BMI experiment, six of the seven participants completed the Motor Imagery Questionnaire – Revised Second Version (MIQ-RS), which is included in the dataset as PDF files. All data are provided in raw form, without filtering or artifact removal, and validation spreadsheets summarizing data availability, synchronization, and electrode placement are included to support transparency and reproducibility.
